1
00:00:44,760 --> 00:00:51,360
"Who are you?"

2
00:00:52,960 --> 00:00:54,920
It's a simple one, right?

3
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:56,880
No. No, not really.

4
00:00:56,920 --> 00:01:00,120
Because if it was,
you wouldn't be here.

5
00:01:00,200 --> 00:01:06,120
You people are going
to find out who you are.

6
00:01:06,200 --> 00:01:10,800
So, you are going to write
a daily Journal.

7
00:01:10,840 --> 00:01:11,800
And guess what?

8
00:01:11,880 --> 00:01:13,360
You'll start the first thing
tomorrow morning.

9
00:01:13,400 --> 00:01:14,560
You're gonna get up,
sit down,

10
00:01:14,640 --> 00:01:17,040
and you are going to tell
the Journal your name,

11
00:01:17,120 --> 00:01:20,760
a bit about yourself,
your life and your world.

12
00:01:22,040 --> 00:01:23,760
"Who...

13
00:01:24,880 --> 00:01:27,240
"am...

14
00:01:28,200 --> 00:01:29,440
...I?"

15
00:01:35,880 --> 00:01:37,720
I shall see you all again
next week.

16
00:01:59,680 --> 00:02:03,280
Journal entry, day one.

17
00:02:03,360 --> 00:02:05,520
My name is Jack Giamoro.

18
00:02:05,600 --> 00:02:08,560
I live in Malibu, California,
with my wife Nina.

19
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:11,560
Nina is...

20
00:02:13,200 --> 00:02:14,960
Nina is...

21
00:02:15,680 --> 00:02:17,840
a good swimmer.

22
00:02:17,920 --> 00:02:19,600
She likes to swim.

23
00:02:19,680 --> 00:02:21,200
We've been married four years,

24
00:02:21,280 --> 00:02:26,040
and she's a very...

25
00:02:26,120 --> 00:02:27,800
strong swimmer.

26
00:02:28,720 --> 00:02:32,080
My father, Ben Giamoro,
lives with us now.

27
00:02:32,160 --> 00:02:34,520
Dad was a movie producer in the '60s,

28
00:02:34,600 --> 00:02:36,760
mostly low-budget
teen car chase movies,

29
00:02:36,800 --> 00:02:38,640
science fiction stuff.

30
00:02:38,720 --> 00:02:39,800
It wasn't what he wanted to do,

31
00:02:39,880 --> 00:02:41,720
but he was strong and bullheaded

32
00:02:41,760 --> 00:02:43,160
and people loved him.

33
00:02:46,120 --> 00:02:48,480
Six months,
two weeks ago today,

34
00:02:48,560 --> 00:02:51,160
Dad had a stroke
that almost killed him.

35
00:02:52,600 --> 00:02:54,360
Dad's...

36
00:02:56,880 --> 00:02:59,160
Dad is getting better.

37
00:02:59,200 --> 00:03:01,800
I am a talent agent.

38
00:03:01,880 --> 00:03:06,000
I help talented people navigate their dreams
through a treacherous world.

39
00:03:07,600 --> 00:03:11,600
I specialize in handling
television writers,

40
00:03:11,680 --> 00:03:14,640
people that would be much better suited
to this assignment than I am.

41
00:03:18,120 --> 00:03:21,000
Some mornings I get to work
and it's easy.

42
00:03:21,080 --> 00:03:24,080
I'm good and calm, relaxed,

43
00:03:24,160 --> 00:03:26,640
ready to face whatever
the day throws at me.

44
00:03:32,040 --> 00:03:34,360
Some mornings I get stuck in traffic, though.

45
00:03:34,440 --> 00:03:35,480
I get stuck in traffic,

46
00:03:35,560 --> 00:03:37,760
and I sit there and think about my life,

47
00:03:37,840 --> 00:03:39,520
about the world,

48
00:03:39,560 --> 00:03:42,440
about what's out there
waiting to take me,

49
00:03:42,480 --> 00:03:46,000
to test me, to destroy me.

50
00:03:46,600 --> 00:03:51,240
On these days,
I get to work Just a tad less friendly.

51
00:03:53,160 --> 00:03:54,600
End of Journal entry.

52
00:04:00,720 --> 00:04:02,160
Good morning.

53
00:04:08,200 --> 00:04:09,360
Partner meeting in ten minutes.

54
00:04:09,440 --> 00:04:10,400
I got it.

55
00:04:10,440 --> 00:04:12,200
Hey, Jack, you need anything?
Coffee, bagel?

56
00:04:12,280 --> 00:04:13,320
No, I'm fine, thank you.

57
00:04:13,400 --> 00:04:14,640
Hey, you see the game yesterday?

58
00:04:14,720 --> 00:04:15,720
It was a good shot.

59
00:04:15,800 --> 00:04:17,280
Last minute.

60
00:04:17,360 --> 00:04:19,080
Lucky, get out.

61
00:04:30,960 --> 00:04:34,520
I think my wife
has been having an affair.

62
00:04:34,600 --> 00:04:36,200
I don't know who it is,

63
00:04:36,240 --> 00:04:40,040
but I think my wife may be
having an affair.

64
00:04:49,520 --> 00:04:51,720
Partner meeting.

65
00:04:51,760 --> 00:04:54,080
Yeah, I'm coming.

66
00:04:55,160 --> 00:04:56,960
Be right there.

67
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:00,360
All right.
We gonna start?

68
00:05:00,400 --> 00:05:01,440
We're waiting for you, Jack.

69
00:05:01,520 --> 00:05:02,840
Are you gonna sit down?

70
00:05:02,920 --> 00:05:04,640
I've got an 11:30 at NBC.
I don't wanna crease this shirt.

71
00:05:04,720 --> 00:05:05,840
Start.

72
00:05:05,920 --> 00:05:07,920
You're a tragic figure.
I swear to God.

73
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:09,320
Do you have that David Lilly lunch today?

74
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:12,120
Yeah, I do, but it's not a lock,
so we'll see.

75
00:05:12,200 --> 00:05:13,800
You'll sign him.
I have faith.

76
00:05:13,840 --> 00:05:15,400
I IMDB'd him last night.

77
00:05:15,480 --> 00:05:18,040
The guy's created seven hit series
and he's still only 35.

78
00:05:18,120 --> 00:05:20,080
He's way too hot for us
not to own him.

79
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:22,120
He's a bucket of money, Jack.
We need him. Make it happen.

80
00:05:22,160 --> 00:05:24,280
I'm aware of that,
thank you very much, guys,

81
00:05:24,360 --> 00:05:24,840
I appreciate it.

82
00:05:24,920 --> 00:05:26,960
I'm Just saying he took the meeting with me
as a favor to me.

83
00:05:27,040 --> 00:05:29,360
So, while I guarantee you
I will sign him,

84
00:05:29,440 --> 00:05:32,120
it may not be today
that I sign him, okay?

85
00:05:32,200 --> 00:05:33,480
- Calm down.
- So, Jack...

86
00:05:33,520 --> 00:05:36,960
what's this adult ed class
you took last night?

87
00:05:38,640 --> 00:05:40,160
Where did you hear about that?

88
00:05:40,240 --> 00:05:42,280
What class are you taking?
Journal writing?

89
00:05:42,320 --> 00:05:43,560
What is that for?

90
00:05:44,560 --> 00:05:46,480
It's a self-exploration technique.

91
00:05:46,520 --> 00:05:48,240
It's meant to make me
a better team player here.

92
00:05:48,320 --> 00:05:50,280
I'll probably be recommending
everybody take the class.

93
00:05:50,320 --> 00:05:51,120
Oh, come on.

94
00:05:51,160 --> 00:05:52,400
You got us in karate,

95
00:05:52,480 --> 00:05:55,160
Kabbalah meetings,
environmental coffees.

96
00:05:55,240 --> 00:05:56,840
Any chance you're gonna
shit-can this thing

97
00:05:56,880 --> 00:05:58,800
so I can sit home one night
and lay around on the couch?

98
00:05:58,880 --> 00:06:01,080
I don't shit-can things.
I finish what I start.

99
00:06:01,160 --> 00:06:03,240
Why don't you Just go to therapy
like normal fucked up people do?

100
00:06:03,320 --> 00:06:05,120
Why don't we start the meeting?

101
00:06:05,200 --> 00:06:06,520
How about that?

102
00:06:06,600 --> 00:06:09,040
Hey! Put the phone down.

103
00:06:09,120 --> 00:06:10,360
Who'd you tell I was
taking that class?

104
00:06:10,440 --> 00:06:11,400
Did you tell Arlene's assistant?

105
00:06:11,480 --> 00:06:12,840
- The truth?
- Yes, the truth.

106
00:06:12,880 --> 00:06:13,800
I think I did.

107
00:06:13,840 --> 00:06:15,560
Lucky, you...
Why would you do that?

108
00:06:15,600 --> 00:06:16,560
That's my private business.

109
00:06:16,640 --> 00:06:19,080
I don't like my personal business
being out in the street, okay?

110
00:06:19,120 --> 00:06:20,720
As a blanket rule,
do not tell anybody

111
00:06:20,800 --> 00:06:23,640
anything about my life ever, okay?

112
00:06:23,720 --> 00:06:24,800
Who else did you tell?

113
00:06:24,880 --> 00:06:27,320
- The truth?
- Yes, Lucky, the truth!

114
00:06:27,400 --> 00:06:28,360
David Lilly's assistant.

115
00:06:28,440 --> 00:06:29,600
Oh, my God!

116
00:06:29,680 --> 00:06:32,080
They wanted to switch lunch
to drinks last night.

117
00:06:32,160 --> 00:06:34,040
I don't know how
you graduated from Harvard.

118
00:06:34,120 --> 00:06:35,720
You have the common sense
of a five-year-old.

119
00:06:35,800 --> 00:06:37,960
If I didn't have so much to do
today, I'd fire you.

120
00:06:40,520 --> 00:06:41,480
Mom, I gotta go.

121
00:06:55,120 --> 00:06:56,040
So, Jack,

122
00:06:56,120 --> 00:06:59,720
what is up with you and this
Journal-writing course?

123
00:06:59,800 --> 00:07:03,160
Come on, man.
What is that?

124
00:07:03,240 --> 00:07:06,520
That's... that's funny that you ask.

125
00:07:06,560 --> 00:07:07,840
That's...

126
00:07:07,920 --> 00:07:09,040
Just something
I'm doing on the side

127
00:07:09,080 --> 00:07:11,560
to try to understand
the writing process better.

128
00:07:11,640 --> 00:07:14,600
Look, man, you know,
what it comes down to is...

129
00:07:14,680 --> 00:07:16,040
I love writers.

130
00:07:16,120 --> 00:07:17,320
That's my life.

131
00:07:17,400 --> 00:07:19,480
I always wanted to be a writer,
but I'm not.

132
00:07:19,560 --> 00:07:22,440
I'm not good enough and... you are.

133
00:07:22,520 --> 00:07:26,160
L... Look, I gotta ask you something.

134
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:29,200
And think about this
before you answer.

135
00:07:30,520 --> 00:07:33,800
David, are you happy?

136
00:07:35,240 --> 00:07:36,720
Well, I'm not doing
anything as drastic

137
00:07:36,800 --> 00:07:38,960
as writing a morning diary.

138
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:42,000
But, yeah.
I stay happy.

139
00:07:42,040 --> 00:07:43,440
You don't have to dress
up in women's clothes

140
00:07:43,480 --> 00:07:44,760
to write in that thing, do you?

141
00:07:49,160 --> 00:07:50,120
That's funny.

142
00:08:11,200 --> 00:08:12,800
- Hey.
- Hey.

143
00:08:12,880 --> 00:08:15,720
- How was your day?
- Brutal.

144
00:08:15,800 --> 00:08:17,160
How was
the scleroderma dinner?

145
00:08:17,240 --> 00:08:19,000
It was good.

146
00:08:22,680 --> 00:08:24,160
Bob Saget was funny.

147
00:08:24,240 --> 00:08:26,720
Where'd you go after that?
I called you a couple times.

148
00:08:26,800 --> 00:08:28,640
You did?

149
00:08:28,680 --> 00:08:30,080
Yeah.

150
00:08:30,120 --> 00:08:31,080
That's weird.

151
00:08:31,160 --> 00:08:33,160
My cell phone was on all night.

152
00:08:33,240 --> 00:08:35,360
Coverage in this city
is so in and out.

153
00:08:35,440 --> 00:08:37,720
What's up with that?

154
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:41,840
Should I read this?
Should I?

155
00:08:41,920 --> 00:08:44,120
No! I don't need
to read this yet.

156
00:08:44,160 --> 00:08:45,640
I don't need to read
any of your Journals.

157
00:08:45,720 --> 00:08:46,720
You know why?

158
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:48,760
Because there's nothing in them.

159
00:08:48,800 --> 00:08:52,680
They're empty, boring,
surface fluff.

160
00:08:55,160 --> 00:08:57,680
First week always is.
Nothing.

161
00:08:57,760 --> 00:09:03,080
Short staccato sentences
masquerading as disclosure.

162
00:09:03,160 --> 00:09:06,520
It's what you know about
yourself without my help.

163
00:09:06,560 --> 00:09:10,560
Your postman knows
more about you than this.

164
00:09:10,640 --> 00:09:12,880
I want more.

165
00:09:12,960 --> 00:09:17,640
This week, I want secrets.

166
00:09:17,720 --> 00:09:19,560
Things other people don't know.

167
00:09:19,640 --> 00:09:23,840
Things you don't know... yet.

168
00:09:23,880 --> 00:09:25,680
Because, you see,

169
00:09:25,760 --> 00:09:30,480
the clues to who you are
are buried in those secrets.

170
00:09:30,560 --> 00:09:36,480
It's like hidden gold under
a twenty-foot pile of horseshit.

171
00:09:36,560 --> 00:09:38,760
Nobody wants to dig through it.
But guess what?

172
00:09:38,840 --> 00:09:40,360
It's in there. The truth.

173
00:09:40,440 --> 00:09:43,600
Waiting patiently under
all the horseshit

174
00:09:43,680 --> 00:09:49,400
that is the build-up
of our silly little lives.

175
00:09:51,800 --> 00:09:54,120
So...

176
00:09:54,200 --> 00:09:56,200
go in and get it, people.

177
00:09:56,280 --> 00:09:58,520
Dig for the truth.

178
00:09:59,640 --> 00:10:01,760
And people, please.

179
00:10:01,800 --> 00:10:03,320
Spelling. It's important.

180
00:10:03,400 --> 00:10:04,600
Get it right.

181
00:10:06,120 --> 00:10:08,520
So...

182
00:10:11,080 --> 00:10:12,760
I'll see you next week.

183
00:10:22,120 --> 00:10:23,840
Hey, Dad.

184
00:10:23,880 --> 00:10:25,880
Hey.

185
00:10:27,320 --> 00:10:29,320
You're up.

186
00:10:29,400 --> 00:10:35,160
This was your mother's favorite show.

187
00:10:54,240 --> 00:10:56,200
I waited too long to marry.

188
00:10:56,280 --> 00:10:58,200
I should have done it in my twenties.

189
00:11:02,280 --> 00:11:04,680
I'm too set in my ways.

190
00:11:04,760 --> 00:11:07,320
I've treated Nina
like a possession,

191
00:11:07,400 --> 00:11:09,880
one of the things I've struggled for,
like my company,

192
00:11:09,960 --> 00:11:12,920
my clients, my abdomen.

193
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:16,600
I work harder on my abdomen
than I do on my marriage.

194
00:11:17,520 --> 00:11:18,280
You know why?

195
00:11:18,360 --> 00:11:20,840
Because this will be
the David Lilly Agency, that's why.

196
00:11:20,880 --> 00:11:22,800
Because every
single person we have here

197
00:11:22,840 --> 00:11:25,480
would be devoted
to advancing your career.

198
00:11:25,520 --> 00:11:26,760
Come on, David.
I talked to you last week.

199
00:11:26,840 --> 00:11:27,880
You said you'd think about it.

200
00:11:27,920 --> 00:11:29,440
You're unrepresented right now.

201
00:11:29,520 --> 00:11:31,880
Yeah, Jack,
I thought it through,

202
00:11:31,920 --> 00:11:34,080
and I'm gonna pass
and say thank you.

203
00:11:34,680 --> 00:11:36,680
All right.
I understand that.

204
00:11:36,760 --> 00:11:38,760
That's perfectly reasonable.

205
00:11:38,840 --> 00:11:39,920
But will you
at least do me the honor

206
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:41,840
of passing to me in person

207
00:11:41,920 --> 00:11:43,840
on the floor of
the Lakers game tonight?

208
00:11:43,920 --> 00:11:46,960
Hold on a second, okay?
Hey, Brynn.

209
00:11:47,040 --> 00:11:48,400
- Brynn.
- What?

210
00:11:48,440 --> 00:11:50,040
You have play rehearsal tonight?

211
00:11:51,480 --> 00:11:53,160
- Why? Who is that?
- It's Jack Giamoro.

212
00:11:53,240 --> 00:11:54,600
He wants to know if I want
to go to the Lakers tonight.

213
00:11:54,640 --> 00:11:56,440
Come on.
The hell he does.

214
00:11:56,520 --> 00:11:58,120
He knows you left your agent.

215
00:11:58,160 --> 00:11:58,960
He Just wants to sign you.

216
00:11:59,040 --> 00:12:01,000
What's going on?

217
00:12:01,080 --> 00:12:02,480
Tell him you have to
take care of the kids.

218
00:12:04,280 --> 00:12:06,880
Listen, Jack, I'm sorry.
I cannot do it tonight.

219
00:12:06,960 --> 00:12:08,800
Brynn is in this play,
and tonight she's got rehearsal,

220
00:12:08,880 --> 00:12:10,280
so I'm stuck with the kids.

221
00:12:10,360 --> 00:12:12,200
The kids.

222
00:12:12,240 --> 00:12:14,160
- Game over.
- I understand that.

223
00:12:14,200 --> 00:12:15,560
It's more important than any of this.
Good for you.

224
00:12:15,600 --> 00:12:17,880
Listen, buddy, I would benefit
from spending some time with you.

225
00:12:17,960 --> 00:12:19,520
What's he saying?

226
00:12:19,600 --> 00:12:22,160
So, Just selfishly,
will you have lunch with me this week?

227
00:12:22,240 --> 00:12:23,880
Okay, Jack.
Sounds great.

228
00:12:23,920 --> 00:12:25,960
Thank you. Okay.

229
00:12:26,040 --> 00:12:27,200
All right, I'll talk to you soon.

230
00:12:27,280 --> 00:12:29,400
Take care of yourself.
All right.

231
00:12:30,840 --> 00:12:33,120
Piece of shit.

232
00:12:33,200 --> 00:12:35,920
Well, he trumped you with
that stuff with the kids.

233
00:12:35,960 --> 00:12:37,960
By the way, the Laker game?
Jack, come on.

234
00:12:38,040 --> 00:12:39,160
You sound like a fool saying that.

235
00:12:39,240 --> 00:12:42,240
Every agency has got
Laker floor seats now, so...

236
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:45,960
Anyway, you've got a bigger problem
than not signing David Lilly.

237
00:12:46,040 --> 00:12:47,280
Phil Balow.

238
00:12:47,320 --> 00:12:48,840
The puppy here was asleep at the wheel.

239
00:12:48,920 --> 00:12:51,280
Whoa, the puppy was not
asleep behind no wheel.

240
00:12:51,320 --> 00:12:53,600
- What happened?
- You put four calls in to the guy.

241
00:12:53,680 --> 00:12:55,280
He hasn't returned one
in three weeks.

242
00:12:55,320 --> 00:12:57,200
Phil Balow's not calling me back?

243
00:12:57,240 --> 00:12:58,480
Jeez, I must have been so crazy,

244
00:12:58,520 --> 00:12:59,560
I didn't even notice.

245
00:12:59,640 --> 00:13:00,720
Didn't we send him something?

246
00:13:00,800 --> 00:13:02,400
That was last month
when he moved downtown.

247
00:13:02,480 --> 00:13:03,760
Phil moved downtown?

248
00:13:03,800 --> 00:13:05,880
Yeah. Him and Sela
got a loft downtown.

249
00:13:05,960 --> 00:13:08,360
I guess they think the Westside
is too white or something.

250
00:13:08,440 --> 00:13:09,680
Downtown?

251
00:13:09,720 --> 00:13:10,480
Yeah, I don't get it either.

252
00:13:10,520 --> 00:13:11,480
You know what?

253
00:13:11,560 --> 00:13:15,480
I don't really get any of this, but, Jack,
fantastic Job signing David Lilly.

254
00:13:15,560 --> 00:13:17,400
It's amazing watching
the master work.

255
00:13:17,480 --> 00:13:18,440
Thanks, Fineberg.

256
00:13:18,520 --> 00:13:20,480
You're the best partner
a guy could ask for.

257
00:13:20,560 --> 00:13:22,680
Sounds to me like you're
about to lose Phil, Jack.

258
00:13:22,760 --> 00:13:23,960
Goddamn it.

259
00:13:33,120 --> 00:13:35,840
Phil Balow was the creator
of the situation comedy,

